               Secondly, I come now to ſhew the neceſſity and victorious efficacy of the grace of God in the converſion of a ſinner. Turn thou me, and I ſhall be turned. This ſhews, (1) The neceſſity of converting grace; as it implies a full conviction, and perſwaſion, "that unleſs

God do turn him by his grace, he ſhall never be turned, but wander endleſly." Again, (2) It ſhews the invincible efficacy of divine grace. God works with a conquering power in converſion; if he gives converting grace, the ſinner, the moſt obſtinate ſinner ſhall be turned. "If he undertake the converſion of a ſoul, it will be converted
                  Mr HENRY.. Let me here ſpeak a word to each of theſe;
